The '''masked booby''' ('''''Sula dactylatra'''''), also called the '''masked gannet''' or the '''blue-faced booby''', is a large [[seabird]] of the [[booby]] and [[gannet]] family, [[Sulidae]]. First described by the French naturalist [[René-Primevère Lesson]] in 1831, the masked booby is one of six species of booby in the genus ''[[Sula (bird)|Sula]]''. It has a typical sulid body shape, with a long pointed yellowish bill, long neck, aerodynamic body, long slender wings and pointed tail. The adult is bright white with black wings, a black tail and a dark face mask; at {{convert|75|-|85|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, it is the largest species of booby. The sexes have similar plumage. This species ranges across tropical oceans, except in the eastern [[Atlantic]] and eastern Pacific. In the latter, it is replaced by the [[Nazca booby]] (''Sula granti''), which was formerly regarded as a [[subspecies]] of masked booby.

Nesting takes place in [[Bird colony|colonies]], generally on islands and [[atoll]]s far from the mainland and close to deep water required for foraging. Territorial when breeding, the masked booby performs [[Agonistic behaviour|agonistic displays]] to defend its nest. Potential and mated pairs engage in courtship and greeting displays. The female lays two chalky white eggs in a shallow depression on flat ground away from vegetation. The chicks are born featherless, but are soon covered in white [[Down feather|down]]. The second chick born generally does not survive and is killed by its elder sibling. These birds are spectacular plunge [[Diving bird|divers]], plunging into the ocean at high speed in search of prey—mainly [[flying fish]]. The species faces few threats; although its population is declining, it is considered to be a [[least-concern species]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN). The masked booby primarily feeds on flying fish and squid, which it captures through high-speed plunge diving.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sula dactylatra (masked booby) {{!}} INFORMATION {{!}} Animal Diversity Web |url=https://animaldiversity.org/accounts/Sula_dactylatra/ |access-date=2026-03-29 |website=animaldiversity.org}}</ref> Breeding Colonies are typically located on remote islands, where reduced predation allows for successful nesting.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Pontier |first=Dominique |last2=Fouchet |first2=David |last3=Bried |first3=Joël |last4=Bahi-Jaber |first4=Nargès |date=2008-06-24 |title=Limited nest site availability helps seabirds to survive cat predation on islands |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304380008000847 |journal=Ecological Modelling |volume=214 |issue=2 |pages=316–324 |doi=10.1016/j.ecolmodel.2008.02.010 |issn=0304-3800|url-access=subscription }}</ref>

== Taxonomy ==
The French naturalist [[René Lesson]] was a member of the crew on the ''[[French ship Astrolabe (1811)|La Coquille]]'', captained by [[Louis Isidore Duperrey]], on its voyage around the world undertaken between August 1822 and March 1825.<ref name=cretella>{{cite journal | last=Cretella | first=Massimo | year=2010 | title=The complete collation and dating of the section ''Zoologie'' of the ''Coquille'' voyage | journal=Bollettino Malacologico | volume=46 | pages=83–103 [83–84] | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51117488 | access-date=30 May 2019 | archive-date=30 May 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530155919/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/51117488 | url-status=live }}</ref> In the multi-volume publication by Duperrey about the voyage, Lesson authored the ornithological sections. In his 1829 account of the visit to [[Ascension Island]] in the [[South Atlantic Ocean]], Lesson mentioned encountering masked boobies, and in a footnote proposed the [[binomial name]] ''Sula dactylatra''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Lesson |first=René |author-link=René Lesson |editor=Duperrey, Louis Isidore |year=1829 |title=Voyage autour du Monde, Exécuté par Ordre du Roi, Sur la Corvette de Sa Majesté, ''La Coquille'', pendant les années 1822, 1823, 1824 et 1825 |language=fr |location=Paris |publisher=Arthus Bertrand |volume=1, Part 2 |page=494 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38661432 |access-date=4 March 2018 |archive-date=10 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181010055829/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/38661432 |url-status=live }} The title page gives the year as 1828 but the ''livraison'' containing page 494 was published in 1829 (See Cretella, 2010)</ref> Lesson subsequently provided a [[species description|formal description]] of the masked booby in 1831.<ref>{{cite book | last=Lesson | first=René | author-link=René Lesson | year=1831 | title=Traité d'Ornithologie, ou Tableau Méthodique | language=fr | place=Paris | publisher=F.G. Levrault | page=601 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35997585 | access-date=30 May 2019 | archive-date=30 May 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530155909/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35997585 | url-status=live }}</ref> The [[specific epithet]] combines the [[Ancient Greek]] {{lang|grc|δάκτυλος}} ({{Transliteration|grc|dáktul}}), meaning {{gloss|finger}}, and the Latin {{lang|la|ater}}, meaning {{gloss|black}}. "Black fingers" refers to the splayed wingtips in flight.<ref name="fraser13">{{cite book |last1=Gray |first1=Jeannie |last2=Fraser |first2=Ian |title=Australian Bird Names: A Complete Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT151 |year=2013 |publisher=Csiro Publishing |location=Collingwood, Victoria |isbn=978-0-643-10471-6 |page=151 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030204902/https://books.google.com/books?id=W1TCqHVWQp0C&pg=PT151#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref> The Swedish zoologist [[Carl Jakob Sundevall]] described the species as ''Dysporus cyanops'' in 1837<ref>{{cite journal | title=''Dysporus cyanops'' | last= Sundevall | first = Carl Jakob | journal=Physiographiska Sällskapets Tidskrift | volume= I | issue= 3| page= 218 [footnote] | year= 1838 | url= https://archive.org/details/physiographiskas00phys/page/218 | language=sv}}</ref> from a [[subadult]] collected in the Atlantic Ocean on 6{{nbsp}}September 1827.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johanson |first1=Kjell Arne |title=NRM 569854 Dysporus cyanops Sundevall, 1838 |url=http://www.nrm.se/forskningochsamlingar/zoologi/samlingar/vertebrater/typsamlingfaglar/icketattingar/sulidae/nrm569854.3441.html |website=Maturhistoriska riksmuseet |access-date=3 March 2019 |language=sv |archive-date=6 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306042642/http://www.nrm.se/forskningochsamlingar/zoologi/samlingar/vertebrater/typsamlingfaglar/icketattingar/sulidae/nrm569854.3441.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The species name was derived from the Ancient Greek words {{lang|grc|κύανος}} ({{Transliteration|grc|kúanos}}), meaning {{gloss|blue}},{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=397}} and {{lang|grc|ὄψ}} ({{Transliteration|grc|óps}}), meaning {{gloss|face}}.{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=804}}

The English ornithologist and bird artist [[John Gould]] described ''Sula personata'' in 1846 from Australia,<ref name="Gould">{{cite journal |author=Gould, John |author-link=John Gould |year=1846 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/12862671 |title=Descriptions of eleven new species of Australian birds |journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London |volume=14 |pages=18–21 |doi=10.1111/j.1469-7998.1846.tb00135.x |access-date=4 March 2018 |archive-date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205103233/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/12862671 |url-status=live }}</ref> the species name being the Latin adjective {{lang|la|personata}}, meaning {{gloss|masked}}.<ref>{{cite book |last=Simpson |first=D.P. |title=Cassell's Latin Dictionary |publisher=Cassell Ltd. |year=1979 |edition=5th |location=London |page=442 |isbn=978-0-304-52257-6}}</ref> Gould adopted the name ''Sula cyanops'' in his 1865 ''[[Handbook to the Birds of Australia]]''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Gould | first=John | author-link=John Gould | year=1865 | title=Handbook to the Birds of Australia | publisher=self-published | place=London | volume=2 | pages=506–507 | url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13966531 | access-date=29 May 2019 | archive-date=29 May 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529141812/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13966531 | url-status=live }}</ref> Sundevall's binomial name was followed as Lesson's 1829 record did not sufficiently describe the species; however, in 1911, the Australian amateur ornithologist [[Gregory Mathews]] pointed out that although Lesson's 1829 account did not describe the bird, his 1831 account did, and thus predated Sundevall by six years, and hence ''Sula dactylactra'' had [[Principle of Priority|priority]].<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3109633 |journal=Novitates Zoologicae |year=1911 |volume=18 |pages=9–10 |title=On some necessary alterations in the nomenclature of birds |first=Gregory |last=Mathews |doi=10.5962/bhl.part.1688 |access-date=4 March 2018 |archive-date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205145730/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/3109633 |url-status=live |doi-access=free }}</ref> The [[American Ornithological Society|American Ornithological Union]] followed in the 17th supplement to their checklist in 1920.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v037n03/p0439-p0449.pdf |title=Seventeenth supplement to the American Ornithologists' Union check-list of North American Birds |journal=Auk |year=1920 |volume=37 |issue=3 |pages=439–449 |doi=10.2307/4073271 |jstor=4073271 |access-date=4 March 2018 |archive-date=22 October 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211022055447/https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v037n03/p0439-p0449.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

[[File:Masked Booby, Grand Turk, TC.jpg|thumb|right|Subsp. ''dactylatra'' In flight, [[Grand Turk Island]]|alt=predominantly white underside of bird in flight]]
"Masked booby" has been designated the official [[common name]] by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]] (IOC).<ref name="ioclist">{{cite web |editor1-last=Gill |editor1-first=Frank |editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) |editor2-last=Donsker |editor2-first=David |year=2025 |title=Storks, frigatebirds, boobies, darters, cormorants |work=World Bird List Version 15.1 |url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/bow/storks/ |publisher=International Ornithologists' Union |access-date=22 July 2025}}</ref> The species has also been called the masked gannet, blue-faced booby, white booby (for its plumage), and whistling booby (for its distinctive call).<ref name="fraser13" /> The Australian ornithologist Doug Dorward promoted the name "white booby" as he felt the blue coloration of its face was less prominent than that of the [[red-footed booby]] (''Sula sula'').{{sfn|Dorward|1962|p=174}}

The masked booby is one of six species of booby in the genus ''[[Sula (bird)|Sula]]''.<ref name="ioclist" /> A 2011 genetic study (''depicted below'') using both [[Nuclear DNA|nuclear]] and [[mitochondrial DNA]] showed the masked and [[Nazca booby|Nazca boobies]] (''Sula granti'') to be each other's closest relatives, their lineage diverging from a line that gave rise to the [[blue-footed booby|blue-footed]] (''Sula nebouxii'') and [[Peruvian booby|Peruvian boobies]] (''Sula variegata''). The masked and Nazca boobies were divergent enough to indicate that the latter, formerly regarded as a [[subspecies]] of the former, should be classified as a separate species. Molecular evidence suggests they most likely diverged between 0.8 and 1.1&nbsp;million years ago. Complex water currents in the eastern Pacific may have established an environmental barrier leading to [[speciation]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Patterson |first1=S.A. |last2=Morris-Pocock |first2=J.A. |last3=Friesen |first3=V.L |year=2011 |title=A multilocus phylogeny of the Sulidae (Aves: Pelecaniformes) |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=58 |issue=2 |pages=181–191 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.11.021 |pmid=21144905 |bibcode=2011MolPE..58..181P }}</ref> Subfossil bones 14,000 years old belonging to the species have been found in deposits on [[Saint Helena|St. Helena]] Island.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/paleornithology23olso|title=Paleornithology of St. Helena Island, South Atlantic Ocean. Smithsonian contributions to paleobiology.Number 23.|author=Olson, Storrs L.|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|year=1975|page=[https://archive.org/details/paleornithology23olso/page/24 24]}}</ref><!-- cites para -->

