===Intraspecific variation and subspecies===
There is a [[Cline (biology)|clinal]] change in size across the masked booby's range. Birds in the Atlantic are the smallest, with the size increasing westwards though the Pacific to the Indian Ocean, where the largest individuals are found.<ref name="hbw">{{cite web |last1=Orta |first1=J. |last2=Jutglar |first2=F. |last3=Garcia |first3=E.F.J. |last4=Kirwan |first4=G.M. |last5=Boesman |first5=P. |editor1-last=del Hoyo |editor1-first=Josep |editor2-last=Elliott |editor2-first=Andrew |editor3-last=Sargatal |editor3-first=Jordi |editor4-last=Christie |editor4-first=David A. |editor5-last=de Juana |editor5-first=Eduardo |year=2017 |title=Masked booby (''Sula dactylatra'') |work=Handbook of the Birds of the World Alive |publisher=Lynx Edicions |url=https://www.hbw.com/species/masked-booby-sula-dactylatra |location=Barcelona, Spain |access-date=2 March 2019 |url-access=subscription |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030204906/https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/masboo/cur/introduction |url-status=live }}</ref> Genetic analysis using [[mtDNA control region]] sequences shows that populations in the Indian and Pacific Oceans greatly expanded around 180,000 years ago, and that these became separated from Atlantic populations around 115,000 years ago. Furthermore, within each ocean, there is evidence of reduced [[gene flow]] between populations that does not correspond with any physical barrier.<ref name=steeves05>{{cite journal |last1=Steeves |first1=Tammy E. |last2=Anderson | first2=David J. | last3=Friesen | first3=Vicki L. |title=A role for nonphysical barriers to gene flow in the diversification of a highly vagile seabird, the masked booby (''Sula dactylatra'') |journal=Molecular Ecology |date=2005 |volume=14 |issue=12 |pages=3877–3887 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-294X.2005.02713.x |pmid=16202102 |bibcode=2005MolEc..14.3877S |s2cid=25708378 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/7563338}}</ref>

Four subspecies are recognized by the International Ornithologists' Union.<ref name="ioclist" />
[[File:Suladactfam3.jpg|thumb|right|A breeding pair of subsp. ''tasmani'' and their chick, [[Norfolk Island]]| alt=Two white birds and a fluffy white chick in long grass with sea in background]]
* ''S. d. dactylatra'' <small>Lesson, 1831</small>
:Breeds in the [[Caribbean]] and some Atlantic islands including [[Ascension Island]]. There is significant genetic divergence between birds on [[Boatswain Bird Island]] off Ascension and those from [[Monito Island]] off Puerto Rico.<ref name=steeves05/>
* ''S. d. melanops'' <small>Hartlaub, 1859</small>
:Breeds in the western Indian Ocean.<ref name="Redman Stevenson Fanshawe 2016">{{cite book |last1=Redman |first1=Nigel |last2=Stevenson |first2=Terry |last3=Fanshawe |first3=John |title=Birds of the Horn of Africa: Ethiopia, Eritrea, Djibouti, Somalia, and Socotra – Revised and Expanded Edition |series=Princeton Field Guides |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton, New Jersey |year=2016 |isbn=978-0-691-17289-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QOs9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA44 |page=44 |access-date=4 December 2018 |archive-date=7 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207205623/https://books.google.com/books?id=QOs9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA44 |url-status=live }}</ref> The German ornithologist [[Gustav Hartlaub]] described this [[taxon]] in 1859 from [[Maydh Island]] off the coast of Somalia near the [[Maydh|town of the same name]]. He noted its black mask and blue-grey feet to be distinct from Sundevall's ''cyanops'' with a blue face, and Lesson's ''dactylatra'' with yellow feet.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The Ibis |year=1859 |volume=1 |issue=4 |url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8610835 |pages=337–352 [351–352] |last=Hartlaub |first=G. |title=List of birds observed and collected during a voyage in the Red Sea |access-date=6 March 2018 |archive-date=5 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205145735/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/8610835 |url-status=live }}</ref> The subspecies name is derived from the Ancient Greek words {{lang|grc|μέλανος}} ({{Transliteration|grc|mélanos}}), meaning {{gloss|black}},{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=431}} and {{lang|grc|ὄψ}} ({{Transliteration|grc|óps}}), meaning {{gloss|face}}.
* ''S. d. tasmani'' <small>van Tets, Meredith, Fullagar & Davidson, 1988</small> (includes ''S.&nbsp;d.&nbsp;fullagari'' as a [[junior synonym]]): Tasman booby
:The form breeding on [[Lord Howe Island|Lord Howe]] and the [[Kermadec Islands]]. The New Zealand naturalist [[Walter Oliver]] had noted that this bird had dark brown rather than pale irises in 1930, but it was not until 1990 that it was formally investigated by R. M. O'Brien and J. Davies and found to also have longer wings than other populations. They classified it as a new subspecies: ''S.&nbsp;d.&nbsp;fullagari''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=O'Brien |first1=R.M. |first2=J. |last2=Davies |title=A new subspecies of Masked Booby ''Sula dactylatra'' from Lord Howe, Norfolk and Kermadec Islands |url=http://marineornithology.org/PDF/18/MO_1990_01.pdf |journal=Marine Ornithology |year=1990 |volume=18 |issue=1 |pages=1–7 |access-date=5 March 2018 |archive-date=27 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427073338/http://www.marineornithology.org/PDF/18/MO_1990_01.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> Meanwhile, large prehistoric specimens known from the Lord Howe and [[Norfolk Island]] had been classified as a separate species, ''S. tasmani'', in 1988, thought to have become extinct due to Polynesian and then European seafarers and settlers.<ref name=vantets88>{{cite journal |last1=van Tets |first1=G.F. |last2=Meredith |first2=C.W. |last3=Fullagar |first3=P.J. |last4=Davidson |first4=P.M. |year=1988 |title=Osteological differences between ''Sula'' and ''Morus'', and a description of an extinct new species of ''Sula'' from Lord Howe and Norfolk Islands, Tasman Sea |journal=Notornis |volume=35 |pages=35–57 [53] |url=https://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_35_1.pdf |access-date=3 March 2018 |archive-date=17 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217201243/https://www.notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_35_1.pdf }}</ref> However, the paleoecologist Richard Holdaway and colleagues cast doubt on the distinctness of the fossil taxon in 2001,<ref>{{cite journal | title=Avifauna from the Emily Bay settlement site, Norfolk Island: a preliminary account |journal=Records of the Australian Museum Supplement |volume=27 |year=2001 |pages=85–100 |last1=Holdaway |first1=Richard |last2=Anderson |first2=Atholl |author2-link=Atholl Anderson |doi=10.3853/j.0812-7387.27.2001.1343 | doi-access=free }}</ref> and a 2010 review by the New Zealand biologist Tammy Steeves and colleagues of the fossil material and DNA found the two overlapped considerably, and hence the extinct and living entities were found to be the same taxon, now known as ''S.&nbsp;d.&nbsp;tasmani'' as this name has priority over ''S.&nbsp;d.&nbsp;fullagari''.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Merging ancient and modern DNA: extinct seabird taxon rediscovered in the North Tasman Sea |first1=Tammy E. |last1=Steeves |first2=Richard N. |last2=Holdaway |first3=Marie L. |last3=Hale |first4=Emma |last4=McLay |first5=Ian A. W. |last5=McAllan |first6=Margaret |last6=Christian |first7=Mark E. |last7=Hauber |first8=Michael |last8=Bunce |doi=10.1098/rsbl.2009.0478 |pmid=19675005 |journal=Biology Letters |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=94–97 |year=2010 |pmc=2817237}}</ref> Fieldwork in the Kermadec Islands indicates the bills of adults are bright yellow, and that adult males had brighter yellow feet than females.<ref name=ismar>{{cite journal |title=Morphology of the recently re-classified Tasman Masked Booby ''Sula dactylatra tasmani'' breeding on the Kermadec Islands |journal=Marine Ornithology |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=105–109 |year=2010 |url=http://eprints.uni-kiel.de/19516/1/38_2_105-109.pdf |first1=Stefanie M. H. |last1=Ismar |first2=Karen |last2=Baird |first3=Selina |last3=Patel |first4=Craig D. |last4=Millar |first5=Mark E. |last5=Hauber |access-date=22 July 2018 |archive-date=22 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180722095717/http://eprints.uni-kiel.de/19516/1/38_2_105-109.pdf }}</ref>
* ''S. d. personata'' <small>Gould, 1846</small> (includes ''S.&nbsp;d.&nbsp;californica'' and ''S.&nbsp;d.&nbsp;bedouti'')
:Breeds in the central and western Pacific and around Australia, as well as off Mexico and on [[Clipperton Island]] in the Pacific Ocean off the coast of Central America. Birds of the latter two locations have been separated as subspecies ''californica'', and the north west Australian population has been named as subspecies ''bedouti'', but neither is usually considered distinct;<ref name="ioclist" /> the American biologist Robert Pitman and colleagues found no consistent differences between these three subspecies.<ref name=pitman1998>{{Cite journal|last1=Pitman|first1=Robert L.|last2=Jehl|first2=Joseph R. Jnr.|year=1998|title=Geographic variation and reassessment of species limits in the "Masked" Boobies of the Eastern Pacific Ocean|jstor=4163925|journal=The Wilson Bulletin|volume=110|issue=2|pages=155–170|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v110n02/p0155-p0170.pdf|access-date=28 May 2019|archive-date=26 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210126215607/https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/wilson/v110n02/p0155-p0170.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Description ==
[[File:Kure Masked Booby juveniles.jpg|thumb|left|Juveniles of subsp ''personata'' on [[Kure Atoll]] in the [[Hawaiian Islands|Hawaiian island]] chain| alt= Seven brownish birds sitting on a large log on a beach]]
The largest species of booby, the masked booby ranges from {{convert|75|to|85|cm|in|abbr=on}} long, with a {{convert|160|-|170|cm|in|abbr=on}} wingspan and {{convert|1.2|-|2.2|kg|lb|abbr=on}} weight. It has a typical [[sulidae|sulid]] body shape, with a long pointed bill, long neck, aerodynamic body, long slender wings and pointed tail. The adult is bright white with dark wings and a dark tail.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}}<!-- cites 3 previous sentences--> The sexes have similar plumage with no seasonal variation, but females are on average slightly heavier and larger than males.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|pp=763, 771–772}}<!--p.763 for similar plumage, p.771 for size, p.772 for weights--> The bare skin around the face, throat and [[Lore (anatomy)|lores]] is described either as black or blue-black. It contrasts with the white plumage and gives a mask-like appearance.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|pp=763, 771}} The bill of the [[nominate subspecies]] is pale yellow with a greenish tinge, sometimes greyish at the base.<ref name="hbw"/> Conical in shape, the bill is longer than the head and tapers to a slightly downcurved tip. Backward-pointing [[serration]]s line the mandibles.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=772}} The [[Flight feather#Primaries|primaries]], [[Flight feather#Secondaries|secondaries]], [[Flight feather#Tertials|humerals]] and [[Flight feather#Rectrices|rectrices]] are brown-black. The inner webs of the secondaries are white at the base. The underwing is white except for the brown-black flight-feathers that are not covered by the white [[Flight feather#Tectrices|coverts]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=770}} The legs are yellow-orange or olive.<ref name="hbw"/> The iris is yellow.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=771}}

The subspecies differ slightly in size and sometimes also in the colour of the irises, bill, legs and feet. The race ''melanops'' has an orange-yellow bill and olive-grey legs, the race ''tasmani'' has dark brown irises and dark grey-green legs and the race ''personata'' has olive to blueish-grey legs.<ref name="hbw"/> For the subspecies ''tasmani'' and the nominate ''dactylatra'', during the breeding season, the leg colour of male birds contains more yellow-red than those of the females.<ref name=ismar/><ref>{{ cite journal | last1=Rull | first1=I.L. | last2=Nicolás | first2=L. | last3=Neri-Vera | first3=N. | last4=Argáez | first4=V. | last5=Martínez | first5=M. | last6=Torres | first6=R. | year=2016 | title=Assortative mating by multiple skin color traits in a seabird with cryptic sexual dichromatism | journal=Journal of Ornithology | volume=157 | issue=4 | pages=1049–1062 | doi=10.1007/s10336-016-1352-4 | bibcode=2016JOrni.157.1049R | s2cid=11376276 }}</ref>

The juvenile is a streaked or mottled grey-brown on the head and upperparts, with a whitish neck collar. The wings are dark brown and underparts are white. Its bill is yellowish, face is blue-grey and iris a dark brown. Older immature birds have a broader white collar and rump,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}} and more and more white feathers on the head until the head is wholly white by 14 to 15 months of age. Full adult plumage is acquired three to four months before the bird turns three years old.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=771}}<!-- cites 2 previous sentences-->

The masked booby is usually silent at sea, but is noisy at the nesting colonies. The main call of male birds is a descending whistle; that of females is a loud honk.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=769}}

The adult masked booby is distinguished from the related Nazca booby by its yellow rather than orange bill, larger size and less distinctive sexual dimorphism. The latter nests on steep cliffs rather than flat ground.<ref name=pitman1998/> The white [[morph (zoology)|morph]] of the red-footed booby is similar but smaller.<ref name="hbw"/> [[Abbott's booby]] (''Papasula abbotti'') has a more wholly black upperwing, and a longer neck and tail and larger head, while the [[Cape gannet]] (''Morus capensis'') and the [[Australasian gannet]] (''Morus serrator'') have a buff-yellow crown, shorter tail, white {{Birdgloss|tertiaries|humerals}} and a grey rather than yellowish bill. The juvenile masked booby resembles the [[brown booby]] (''Sula leucogaster''), though adults of that species have clearly demarcated brown and white plumage.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}}

== Distribution and habitat ==
The masked booby is found across tropical oceans between the [[30th parallel north]] and [[30th parallel south]]. In the Indian Ocean it ranges from the coastlines of the Arabian Peninsula and East Africa across to Sumatra and Western Australia, though it is not found off the coast of the Indian subcontinent. Off the Western Australian coastline it is found as far south as the [[Dampier Archipelago]]. In the Pacific, it ranges from Brisbane eastwards. It is found in the Caribbean and Atlantic Ocean south to Ascension Island.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=764}}<!-- cites para --> In the eastern Pacific off the coast of Colombia and Ecuador, the masked booby is replaced by the Nazca booby.<ref name=pitman1998/> A [[Vagrancy (biology)|vagrant]] was rescued in 2015 in [[Newport, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Rare Tropical Booby fills up on Northwest Seafood, Catches Flight South |url=https://aquarium.org/tag/masked-booby/ |publisher=Oregon Coast Aquarium |date=7 October 2015 |access-date=1 June 2019 |archive-date=1 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601211908/https://aquarium.org/tag/masked-booby/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In the Atlantic, Caribbean birds occasionally wander north to warm southern [[Gulf Stream]] waters off the eastern seaboard of the United States, with single records from [[Island Beach State Park|Island Beach]] in New Jersey and New York.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Boyle |first1=William J. Jr. |title=The Birds of New Jersey: Status and Distribution |date=2011 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton, New Jersey |isbn=978-1-4008-3828-8 |page=51 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5ejUSy8sn5cC&pg=PA51 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030204906/https://books.google.com/books?id=5ejUSy8sn5cC&pg=PA51#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref> There are summer records from [[Delaware Bay]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Brady |first1=Alan |title=Atlantic Seabird Photo Journal: Off New York, New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland Coasts to Canyons 1967–2006 |date=2009 |publisher=Xlibris Corporation |location=Bloomington IN |isbn=978-1-4500-8159-7 |pages=75–76 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MPDwZPQtD-8C&pg=PA75 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030204906/https://books.google.com/books?id=MPDwZPQtD-8C&pg=PA75#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Worcester County, Maryland]],<ref>{{cite book |last1=Beehler |first1=Bruce M. |title=Birds of Maryland, Delaware, and the District of Columbia |date=2019 |publisher=JHU Press |location=Baltimore, Maryland |isbn=978-1-4214-2733-1 |page=365 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=odWLDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA365 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030204908/https://books.google.com/books?id=odWLDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA365#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref> as well as waters off the coast of Spain.<ref name=Peterson1967>{{Cite book |last1=Peterson |first1=Roger Tory |last2=Mountfort |first2=Guy |last3=Hollom |first3=P.A.S. |year=2001 |orig-date=1967 |title=A Field Guide to the Birds of Britain and Europe |page=241 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=s12BdfjtWtsC&pg=PA241 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |location=New York |isbn=978-0-618-16675-6 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030205410/https://books.google.com/books?id=s12BdfjtWtsC&pg=PA241#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref>

During the monsoon season (midyear), the masked booby is an occasional vagrant along the western coast of India, with records from [[Kerala]], Karnataka,<ref>{{cite journal|author=Madhyastha, N.A.|year=1987|title=First report of masked booby ''Sula dactylara'' from the shores of coastal Karnataka|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/49081508|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=84|page=434|access-date=13 June 2019|archive-date=28 March 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210328130706/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/49081508|url-status=live}}</ref> and [[Maharashtra]] states.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Recent records of masked booby (''Sula dactylatra'') along the western coast of India |first=Raju |last=Kasambe |journal=Newsletter for Birdwatchers |pages=59–60 |volume=50 |issue=4 |year=2010 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/265652060 }}</ref> It is a vagrant to the [[Caroline Islands]] north of New Guinea.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wiles |first1=G.J. |first2=D.J. |last2=Worthington |first3=R.E. |last3=Beck, Jr. |first4=H.D. |last4=Pratt |first5=C.F. |last5=Aguon |first6=R.L. |last6=Pyle |year=2000 |title=Noteworthy bird records for Micronesia, with a summary of raptor sightings in the Mariana Islands, 1988–1999 |journal=Micronesica |volume=32 |issue=2 |pages=257–284 [260] |url=http://micronesica.org/sites/default/files/16_wiles_etal.pdf |access-date=26 April 2018 |archive-date=22 April 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180422033603/http://micronesica.org/sites/default/files/16_wiles_etal.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Breeding colonies ===
[[File:Starr 060228-6311 Chenopodium oahuense.jpg|thumb|right|Breeding sites in areas relatively free of vegetation, Oahu| alt=Birds nesting across a flat rocky area near the sea]]
Breeding colonies are located on remote islands, atolls and cays.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}} Lord Howe Island is the southernmost colony.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=764}} Deep water nearby is important for feeding. As an example, waters around [[Raine Island]], at the edge of the [[Great Barrier Reef]], are anywhere from {{convert|180|to|3700|m|ft|abbr=on}} deep.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}} On these landforms, masked boobies select sites of generally flat, bare or exposed open ground that lie above the high-tide level with access to the ocean.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=764}} During the breeding season, the species remains near the colony. At other times, juveniles and some adults disperse widely, though some remain at the colony year-round. Most (but not all) birds return to breed at the colony of their birth; once they begin breeding at a site, they will return there annually.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}}<!-- cites previous 3 sentences-->

The largest masked booby colony is on Clipperton Island in the eastern Pacific Ocean,<ref name="hbw"/> a desert atoll southwest of Mexico. In 2003, 112,000 birds were counted, having recovered from 150 individuals in 1958. The population had suffered from the introduction of [[feral pigs]] in the 1890s. These pigs preyed on the crabs that ate the vegetation. After the elimination of pigs in 1964, the crab population rose and vegetation largely disappeared. This was beneficial to the boobies, as they prefer open ground.<ref name="Pitman et al. 2005">{{cite journal |last1=Pitman |first1=Robert L. |first2=Lisa T. |last2=Ballance |first3=Charly |last3=Bost |year=2005 |title=Clipperton Island: pigsty, rat hole and booby prize |journal=Marine Ornithology |url=http://mundo.cabrillo.edu/~ncrane/Clipperton/ratsandpigs.pdf |volume=33 |issue=2 |pages=193–194 |access-date=1 March 2019 |archive-date=19 November 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201119121316/http://mundo.cabrillo.edu/~ncrane/Clipperton/ratsandpigs.pdf }}</ref> Clipperton is on a narrow ridge surrounded by deep water.<ref name="Weimerskirch08">{{cite journal |last1=Weimerskirch |first1=Henri |first2=Matthieu |last2=Le Corre |first3=Charles A. |last3=Bost |title=Foraging strategy of masked boobies from the largest colony in the world: relationship to environmental conditions and fisheries |journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series |date=2008 |volume=362 |pages=291–302 |doi=10.3354/meps07424 |url=https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps2008/362/m362p291.pdf |bibcode=2008MEPS..362..291W |doi-access=free |access-date=31 May 2019 |archive-date=10 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200810185743/https://www.int-res.com/articles/meps2008/362/m362p291.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The colony on Lord Howe Island numbered in the thousands at the time of the island's discovery in 1788, but has declined to under 500 pairs—mostly on offshore islets with the remainder on two hard-to-access headlands—by 2005. Hunting by humans is thought to have played a role; although rats were introduced to the island in 1918, there has been no evidence they are able to kill chicks or eggs—possibly due to the size of the adult boobies.<ref name=Priddel05>{{cite journal |last1=Priddel |first1=David |first2=Ian |last2=Hutton |first3=Samantha|last3= Olson |first4= Robert |last4=Wheeler | title=Breeding biology of Masked Boobies (''Sula dactylatra tasmani'') on Lord Howe Island, Australia |journal=Emu |date=2005 |volume=105 |issue=2 |pages=105–113 |doi=10.1071/MU04028|bibcode=2005EmuAO.105..105P |s2cid=55658891 }}</ref> The masked booby was first recorded breeding on [[Phillip Island (Norfolk Island)|Philip Island]] off Norfolk Island in 1908, with devegetation by feral animals creating the open ground preferred by the species. By 2007, an estimated 300 pairs were breeding over the island, though the island flora's regeneration after the removal of feral animals might begin to limit suitable nesting sites.<ref name=priddel10>{{cite journal |last1=Priddel |first1=David |first2=Nicholas |last2=Carlile |first3=Olwyn |last3=Evans |first4=Beryl |last4=Evans |first5=Honey |last5=McCoy |title=A review of the seabirds of Phillip Island in the Norfolk Island Group |journal=Notornis |date=2010 |volume=57 |pages=113–127 |url=http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Priddel%20et%20al.%202010.pdf |access-date=2 June 2019 |archive-date=21 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210221161051/http://notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Priddel%20et%20al.%202010.pdf }}</ref> In 2006, two pairs nested in a brown booby colony on Morros del Potosí (White Friars Rocks) near [[Zihuatanejo]] in southern Mexico.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Castillo-Guerrero |first1=Alfredo |first2=Juan Pablo |last2=Ceyca |first3=Eric |last3=Mellink |title=A nesting record of the Masked Booby from Guerrero, Southern Mexico |journal=Western Birds |date=2007 |volume=38 |pages=229–231 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235654578 |access-date=4 July 2019 |archive-date=28 March 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210328130840/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/235654578_A_nesting_record_of_the_Masked_Booby_from_Guerrero_Southern_Mexico |url-status=live }}</ref>

Major nesting areas in the Atlantic include [[Rocas Atoll]] off the coast of Brazil,<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Mancini | first1=P.L. | last2=Serafini | first2=P.P. | last3=Bugoni | first3=L. | year=2016 | title=Breeding seabird populations in Brazilian oceanic islands: historical review, update and a call for census standardization | journal=Revista Brasileira de Ornitologia | volume=24 | issue=2 | pages=94–115 [99] | doi=10.1007/BF03544338 | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/308878960 | doi-access=free | access-date=6 June 2020 | archive-date=28 March 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210328130840/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/308878960_Breeding_seabird_populations_in_Brazilian_oceanic_islands_Historical_review_update_and_a_call_for_census_standardization | url-status=live }}</ref> Ascension Island in the south Atlantic,<ref name=ratcliffe/><!--4,500 pairs--> and five islands of the [[Campeche Bank]] in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].<ref>{{ cite report | last1=Tunnell | first1=John W. | last2=Chapman | first2=Brian R.| year=2000 | title=Seabirds of the Campeche Bank Islands, southeastern Gulf of Mexico | series=Atoll Research Bulletin No. 482 | location=Washington DC | publisher=Smithsonian | hdl=10088/4870 | hdl-access=free }}<!--4,519 active nests on five of the islands--></ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Morales-Vera | first1=T.E. | last2=Ruz-Rosado | first2=F.D. | last3=Velarde | first3=E. | last4=Keith | first4=E.O. | year=2017 | title=Status of seabird nesting populations on Arrecife Alacranes, Gulf of Mexico | journal=Marine Ornithology | volume=45 | pages=175–185 | url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/45_2_175-185_0.pdf | access-date=11 June 2019 | archive-date=13 April 2021 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210413002641/https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/45_2_175-185_0.pdf | url-status=live }}</ref> The species attempted to nest at [[Dry Tortugas]] in the Gulf of Mexico over 1984 and 1985;<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Clapp |first1=Roger | first2= William B. Jr | last2=Robertson |title=Nesting of the Masked Booby on the Dry Tortugas, Florida: The first record for the contiguous United States |journal=Colonial Waterbirds |date=1986 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=113–116 |doi=10.2307/1521152|jstor=1521152 |bibcode=1986ColWa...9..113C }}</ref> 19 pairs were recorded there in 1998.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dry Tortugas National Park |url=https://www.audubon.org/important-bird-areas/dry-tortugas-national-park |publisher=National Audubon Society |access-date=1 June 2019 |date=2016-09-12 |archive-date=8 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220208174226/https://www.audubon.org/important-bird-areas/dry-tortugas-national-park |url-status=live }}</ref>

