The masked booby generally flies at least {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} in height, and at speeds of up to {{convert|70|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}. It alternates between gliding and active flying with strong periodic wingbeats. It is often encountered alone, or in a small group when returning to its colony.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=763}}<!-- cites 2 preceding sentences -->

Regarding the masked booby's longevity, a bird tagged at [[Nepean Island (Norfolk Island)|Nepean Island]] (off Norfolk Island) in September 1979 was recovered and released after being caught in fishing gear 24 years and 9.9 months later some {{cvt|713|km}} away off the [[Isle of Pines (New Caledonia)|Isle of Pines]], New Caledonia in July 2004. The longest distance travelled is {{cvt|3152|km}}; a bird tagged at Raine Island in the [[Great Barrier Reef]] in December 1981 was picked up and released at Phillip Island (off Norfolk Island) in December 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/biodiversity/abbbs/abbbs-search.pl?taxon_id=1021|title=ABBBS Database Search: Sula dactylatra (Masked booby)|last=Australian Bird & Bat Banding Scheme (ABBBS)|date=2018|work=Bird and bat banding database|publisher=Australian Government Department of the Environment and Energy|access-date=1 June 2019|archive-date=30 October 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030205417/http://www.environment.gov.au/cgi-bin/biodiversity/abbbs/abbbs-search.pl?taxon_id=1021|url-status=live}}</ref><!-- cites previous two sentences -->

===Breeding and courtship===
The masked booby begins breeding by around four or five years of age, though can occasionally do so at three years old.<ref name=florida/> Adults form [[Monogamy in animals|monogamous]] relationships with many pairs remaining together over multiple breeding seasons. Highly territorial when nesting, single males and mated pairs engage in [[Agonistic behaviour|agonistic displays]] to mark their ground against neighbours and interlopers. The male advertises his territory to females by ''flight circuiting''—making a short flight and holding his wings in a 'V' shape and making a call as he lands. The mated pair engages in ''outposting'' as other boobies fly overhead, stretching their necks out and forward. More direct trespassers are confronted with a ''yes-no headshaking'', in which the booby shakes its head from side to side or up and down and ruffles its head feathers to make its head look bigger and facial markings more prominent. It may cock its tail and hold its wings up away from its body.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=767}}<!-- cites 3 preceding sentences --> Neighbouring boobies may escalate by jabbing and lunging at each other. In the ''pelican posture'', a bird tucks the tip of its bill into its chest, possibly positioned to avoid injury to others. This posture is used against intruders or as advertising for a mate.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=768}}<!-- cites 2 preceding sentences -->

There are several displays related to the establishment and maintenance of pair-bonding. The male initiates ''sky-pointing'' when a female approaches or leaves his territory. In this display, he paces slowly with his neck and bill pointed upwards—between vertical and 45 degrees—with wings partly raised and whistling faintly with an open bill. In a ''gazing'' display, one bird stares at another of the opposite sex; this generally leads to other displays. Pairs engage in a (mostly) gentler form of jabbing display, and [[Preening (bird)#Allopreening|allopreening]]. In an ''oblique headshake'', a bird flings its head vigorously. The male may also parade in front of the female, walking with an exaggerated high-stepping gait and intermittently tucking his head in his breast, after collecting nesting material and before the pair begins laying. The male presents small sticks and debris as nesting material in a gesture of symbolic nest-building, which leads to copulation. Afterwards, the pair engages in more symbolic nest-building.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=768}}<!-- cites para --> The twigs and debris are cleared away later as none is actually used in adorning the nest while in use.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=769}}

Breeding takes place at different times of year throughout its range. On the [[Cocos (Keeling) Islands]], egg-laying takes place from January to July, peaking in June, with juvenile birds from April to December. On Moulter Cay in the [[Coral Sea]], breeding takes place year-round, with egg-laying peaking from September to early November, while on nearby Raine Island birds begin laying in or after August, likely peaking September to early November.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=769}} Eggs are laid between May and September on Lord Howe Island,<ref name=Priddel05/> and early July to early January (peaking in September) on Phillip Island.<ref name=priddel10/>

In the northern hemisphere, egg-laying on [[Kure Atoll]] can be any time from January to early July, peaking in February and March.<ref name=woodward72>{{cite journal | last=Woodward | first=Paul W. | year=1972 | title=The natural history of Kure Atoll, Northwestern Hawaiian Islands | journal=Atoll Research Bulletin| volume=164 | issue=164 | pages=1–318 [148–167] | hdl=10088/6078 | doi=10.5479/si.00775630.164.1 }}</ref> On Clipperton Island, egg-laying peaks in November to coordinate with peak fish productivity of the surrounding waters in January (for growing chicks).<ref name="Weimerskirch08"/> Masked boobies lay at any time in the Caribbean, peaking between March and September.<ref name=florida>{{cite book |last1=Nellis |first1=David W. |title=Common Coastal Birds of Florida and the Caribbean |date=2001 |publisher=Pineapple Press Inc |location=Sarasota, Florida |isbn=978-1-56164-191-8 |pages=95–97 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-REZ4R8wBg4C&pg=PA95 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030205413/https://books.google.com/books?id=-REZ4R8wBg4C&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref>

The nest is a cleared area {{cvt|0.75|to|1|m}} in diameter, within which is a clearly demarcated {{cvt|25|to|30|cm|0}} shallow ({{cvt|1|-|2|cm|1}} deep) depression. A clutch of two chalky white eggs is laid, with an interval of five to eight days between the laying of each egg. Occasionally nests with three eggs are reported; these are probably due to an egg from another nest rolling downhill into the nest.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=769}}<!-- cites previous 3 sentences --> The eggs have an average size of {{cvt|64|x|45|mm}} and weigh {{cvt|75|g}}.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=769}} They are incubated by both adults for 45 days.<ref name=Priddel05/> Parents incubate the eggs by resting on their {{Birdgloss|tarsi}} and wrapping their webbed feet over the eggs, with the outermost toes resting on the ground. Their feet are more vascular at this time.{{sfn|Dorward|1962|pp=185–186}} When first hatched, the chicks are about {{cvt|10|cm}} long and weigh around {{cvt|40|-|60|g}}, with a sparse covering of white down over their grey to pinkish-grey skin. [[Altricial]] and [[nidicolous]], their eyes are open at birth. Their down thickens as they age, and the chicks are quite fluffy by week 5–6. The primaries and rectrices appear by week 8, and {{Birdgloss|scapulars}} appear by week 10. They begin losing their down from week 12 onwards, until they are wholly covered by juvenile plumage by week 15 or 16, and [[fledge]] at around 120 days (17 weeks) of age.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=770}} After leaving the nest, young birds are dependent on their parents for 3–4 weeks before dispersing out to sea.{{sfn|Dorward|1962|p=179}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/breedingbiologyo00kepl |title=Breeding Biology of the Blue-faced Booby (Sula dactylatra personata) on Green Island, Kure Atoll|last=Kepler | first=Cameron B.|publisher=Nuttall Ornithology Club|year=1969|place=Cambridge, MA | oclc=248142 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/breedingbiologyo00kepl/page/33 33]–34 }}</ref>

Although two eggs are often laid, the younger chick almost always perishes within a few days. This has been observed widely across the species' range. Dorward suspected [[siblicide]] on Ascension Island.{{sfn|Dorward|1962|pp=194–197}} Siblicide has been observed in the Nazca booby on the [[Galapagos Islands]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Anderson |first1=Atholl |author1-link=Atholl Anderson |title=The role of parents in sibilicidal brood reduction of two booby species |journal=The Auk |year=1995 |volume=112 |issue=4 |pages=860–869 |doi=10.2307/4089018 |jstor=4089018 |url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v112n04/p0860-p0869.pdf |access-date=28 May 2019 |archive-date=28 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190528134502/https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/auk/v112n04/p0860-p0869.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> and is assumed to occur in the masked booby as well.{{sfn|Dorward|1962|pp=194–197}}<ref name=Priddel05/>

=== Feeding ===
[[File:Cheilopogon melanurusPCCA20070623-3956B.jpg|thumb|left|Flying fish, such as the [[Atlantic flyingfish]], are a common prey item.]]
The masked booby is a spectacular diver, plunging vertically or near-vertically from heights of anywhere from {{convert|12|to|100|m|ft|abbr=on|round=5}}—but more commonly {{convert|15|to|35|m|ft|abbr=on|round=5}}—above the water into the ocean at high speed, to depths of up to {{convert|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} in search of fish.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=765}} It generally swallows its catch underwater.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=766}} Fieldwork at Clipperton Island showed that masked boobies flew on average to {{convert|103|km|mi|abbr=on}} from their colony, with a maximum range of {{convert|242|km|mi|abbr=on}}, while feeding their chicks. They did not rest at sea at night, though part of their return trip was at night time for longer expeditions.<ref name="Weimerskirch08"/> The masked booby forages with the [[white-bellied storm petrel]] (''Fregetta grallaria'') and [[Bulwer's petrel]] (''Bulweria bulwerii'') at times.<ref>{{cite journal |first1=David G. |last1=Ainley |first2=Robert J. |last2=Boekelheide |title=An ecological comparison of oceanic seabird communities of the South Pacific Ocean |journal=Studies in Avian Biology |year=1984 |volume=8 |pages=2–23 [18] |url=https://sora.unm.edu/node/139193 |access-date=6 March 2018 |archive-date=11 August 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200811193408/https://sora.unm.edu/node/139193 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Frigatebird]]s often harass the species until they disgorge their catch and steal their food.<ref name="hbw" />

Fish, particularly [[flying fish]], up to {{convert|28|cm|in|abbr=on}} long (rarely up to {{convert|41|cm|in|abbr=on}}) form the bulk of its diet, along with [[cephalopod]]s.<ref name="hbw" /> Species eaten include various species of flying fish such as [[blue flyingfish]] (''Exocoetus volitans''), [[mirrorwing flyingfish]] (''Hirundichthys speculiger''), [[sailfin flyingfish]] (''Parexocoetus brachypterus''), [[Cheilopogon atrisignis|glider flyingfish]] (''Cheilopogon atrisignis'') and [[Atlantic flyingfish]] (''Cheilopogon melanurus''), other fish such as [[yellowtail amberjack]] (''Seriola lalandi''), [[skipjack tuna]] (''Katsuwonus pelamis''), [[mackerel scad]] (''Decapterus macarellus''), [[pompano dolphinfish]] (''Coryphaena equiselis''), [[mahi-mahi]] (''Coryphaena hippurus''), [[brown chub]] (''Kyphosus bigibbus''), [[redbarred hawkfish]] (''Cirrhitops fasciatus''), [[snake mackerel]] (''Gempylus serpens''), [[frigate tuna]] (''Auxis thazard''), [[Pacific saury]] (''Cololabis saira''), [[Euleptorhamphus viridis|ribbon halfbeak]] (''Euleptorhamphus viridis''), [[flat needlefish]] (''Ablennes hians'') and mullet of the genus ''[[Mugil]]'', and the [[Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis|purpleback flying squid]] (''Sthenoteuthis oualaniensis'').{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1990|p=766}}<!-- cites para -->

==Predators and parasites==
[[Silver gull]]s (''Chroicocephalus novaehollandiae'') and [[buff-banded rail]]s (''Gallirallus philippensis'') prey on eggs and young. On some islands such as Ascension and Saint Helena, feral cats have been a threat to masked boobies.<ref name=ratcliffe>{{cite journal | last1=Ratcliffe | first1=Norman | last2=Bella | first2=Mike | last3=Pelembe | first3=Tara | last4=Boyle | first4=Dave | last5=Benjamin | first5=Raymond | last6=White | first6=Richard | last7=Godley | first7=Brendan | last8=Stevenson | first8=Jim | last9=Sanders | first9=Sarah | year=2010 | title=The eradication of feral cats from Ascension Island and its subsequent recolonization by seabirds | journal=Oryx | volume=44 | issue=1 | pages=20–29 | doi=10.1017/S003060530999069X | s2cid=51902194 | url=http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/Ratcliffe-et-al-2009-The-eradication-of-feral-cats-from-Ascension-Island-and-its-subsequent-recolonization-by-seabirds.pdf | doi-access=free | access-date=2 June 2019 | archive-date=2 February 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202210602/http://www.ascension-island.gov.ac/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/Ratcliffe-et-al-2009-The-eradication-of-feral-cats-from-Ascension-Island-and-its-subsequent-recolonization-by-seabirds.pdf | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Bolton | first1=M. | last2=Watt | first2=R. | last3=Fowler | first3=E. | last4=Henry | first4=L. | last5=Clingham | first5=E. | year=2011 | title=Re-colonisation and successful breeding of masked boobies ''Sula dactylatra'' on mainland St Helena, South Atlantic, in the presence of feral cats ''Felis catus'' | journal=Seabird | volume=24 | pages=60–71 | doi=10.61350/sbj.24.60 | s2cid=131226663 | url=http://www.seabirdgroup.org.uk/journals/seabird-24/seabird-24-60.pdf | access-date=2 June 2019 | archive-date=2 June 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602122927/http://www.seabirdgroup.org.uk/journals/seabird-24/seabird-24-60.pdf | url-status=live }}</ref> The tick species ''Ornithodoros (Alectorobius) muesebecki'' was described parasitising nesting blue-faced boobies off the Arabian coast.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Hoogstraal, Harry|year=1969|title=''Ornithodoros'' (''Alectorobius'') ''muesebecki'' n. sp., a parasite of the blue-faced booby (''Sula dactylatra melanops'') on Hasikiya Island, Arabian Sea|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/16277876|journal=Proceedings of the Entomological Society of Washington|volume=71|pages=368–374|access-date=13 June 2019|archive-date=15 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415115833/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/16277876|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Argasidae|argasid]] tick ''[[Ornithodoros capensis]]'' and the [[Ixodidae|ixodid]] tick ''[[Amblyomma loculosum]]'' have also been recorded as parasites, the latter possibly spreading [[Babesiosis|piroplasmosis]] caused by ''[[Babesia]]'' among boobies.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Peirce|first1=M.A.|last2=Feare|first2=C.J.|year=1978|title=Piroplasmosis in the masked booby ''Sula dactylatra melanops'' in the Amirantes, Indian Ocean|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40824665|journal=Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club|volume=98|pages=38–40|access-date=13 June 2019|archive-date=20 March 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220320145054/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/40824665|url-status=live}}</ref> On Raine Island and Pandora Cay, nests have been destroyed by [[green sea turtle]]s (''Chelonia mydas'') as they pass through booby colonies and dig their own nests in large numbers.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=King |first1=B.R. |title=Seabird Islands No. 43/1 – Raine Island, Great Barrier Reef, Queensland |journal=Corella |date=1986 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=73–77 |url=https://absa.asn.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/C10373.pdf |access-date=13 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190415111354/https://www.absa.asn.au/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/C10373.pdf |archive-date=15 April 2019 }}</ref> Rats prey on eggs and young of many seabirds, though the size of masked boobies probably prevents direct predation. Seabird colonies may experience indirect ecological consequences from the introduction of rats. Research on the ecosystems of the Aleutian Islands has demonstrated that invasive Norway rats modify food-web dynamics by decreasing seabird populations and altering the organization of coastal communities; the recovery of seabird populations and the surrounding marine ecosystems has been linked to the removal of rats.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Le Corre |first=M. |last2=Danckwerts |first2=D. K. |last3=Ringler |first3=D. |last4=Bastien |first4=M. |last5=Orlowski |first5=S. |last6=Morey Rubio |first6=C. |last7=Pinaud |first7=D. |last8=Micol |first8=T. |date=2015-05-01 |title=Seabird recovery and vegetation dynamics after Norway rat eradication at Tromelin Island, western Indian Ocean |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0006320714004881 |journal=Biological Conservation |series=Special Issue on Tropical Island Conservation: Rat Eradication for Species Recovery |volume=185 |pages=85–94 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2014.12.015 |issn=0006-3207|url-access=subscription }}</ref> On Clipperton Island, rats prey on the crab that eats vegetation.<ref name="Pitman et al. 2005"/>

== Relationship with humans ==
The [[Taíno]] ate masked and red-footed boobies that nested on [[Grand Turk Island]] around 1000 years ago. The two species subsequently vanished from the Turks and Caicos Islands. A booby yielded around 1–2&nbsp;kg (2–5&nbsp;lb) of meat. European sailors in the area also caught and ate tame boobies.<ref>{{cite book | title=Talking Taino: Caribbean Natural History from a Native Perspective | first1=William F. | last1=Keegan | first2=Lisabeth A. | last2=Carlson | page=44 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qy8LESKyJS0C&pg=PA44 | publisher=University of Alabama Press | location=Tuscaloosa | year=2008 | isbn=978-0-8173-5508-1 | access-date=6 June 2020 | archive-date=30 October 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030205414/https://books.google.com/books?id=Qy8LESKyJS0C&pg=PA44#v=onepage&q&f=false | url-status=live }}</ref> Masked booby young and eggs were eaten by the crew of {{HMS|Supply|1759|6}} on Lord Howe Island.<ref name=vantets88/>

==Conservation status==
The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) lists the masked booby as a species of [[least concern]], though the population worldwide is decreasing.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> At Clipperton Island, the colony was benefitted by the presence of [[yellowfin tuna]] (''Thunnus albacares''), which drove their prey item—flying fish—to the surface, facilitating predation by boobies. It may be that overfishing of tuna adversely impacts the availability of fish there.<ref name="Weimerskirch08"/> In 2005, 508 young masked boobies at the colony suffered from "[[angel wing]]", a congenital deformity of one or both wings resulting in flightlessness. This coincided with a season of high nestling mortality that was likely related to low numbers of yellowfin tuna due to possible overfishing at a crucial time in the breeding season.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pitman |first1=Robert L. | first2= Lisa T. | last2=Ballance | first3=Charles A. | last3=Bost |title=Incidence of Wing Deformities ('Angel Wing') Among Masked Boobies at Clipperton Island: Life History Consequences and Insight into Etiology |journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology |date=2012 |volume=124 |issue=3 |pages=597–602 | jstor=23324568 | doi=10.1676/11-208.1|s2cid=85187886 }}</ref> The warm phase ([[El Niño]]) of the [[El Niño–Southern Oscillation]] in 1982 and 1983 negatively impacted breeding on Christmas Island as the higher water temperatures reduced food supply. Where usually 1500 pairs nested, no young were observed over this period; 50–60 pairs were observed breeding in October 1983.<ref name="Schreiber84">{{cite journal |last1=Schreiber |first1=Ralph W. |last2=Schreiber |first2=Elizabeth Anne |title=Central Pacific Seabirds and the El Niño Southern Oscillation: 1982 to 1983 Perspectives |journal=Science |date=1984 |volume=225 |issue=4663 |pages=713–716 | jstor=1693159|doi=10.1126/science.225.4663.713 |pmid=17810291 |bibcode=1984Sci...225..713S |s2cid=40459951 }}</ref> The Australian government has rated both subspecies occurring in Australian waters as [[Climate change vulnerability|vulnerable to climate change]]. The low-lying colonies of subspecies ''personata'' are at risk from rising sea levels, and the rising sea temperatures are calculated to reduce food productivity, which may impact on breeding success of both subspecies.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Garnett |first1=Stephen |first2=Donald |last2=Franklin |title=Climate Change Adaptation Plan for Australian Birds |date=2014 |publisher=Csiro Publishing |location=Collingwood, Victoria |isbn=978-0-643-10803-5 |page=111 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=607nAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA111 |access-date=6 June 2020 |archive-date=30 October 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231030205916/https://books.google.com/books?id=607nAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA111#v=onepage&q&f=false |url-status=live }}</ref>

